04488nam a22006735i 9781487577759DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191982onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875777597 a10.3138/97814875777592doi  a(DE-B1597)537023  a(OCoLC)1102108513  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBR1610b.N48 1982eb 7aREL0280002bisacsh04a261.7/22191 aNewman, Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFoundations of Religious Tolerance /cJay Newman. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1982  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1. The concept of religious tolerance -- t2. The concept of religious prejudice -- t3. Tolerance without relativism -- t4. Religious pluralism -- t5. Proselytizing and intolerance -- t6. Exclusivism and universalism -- t7. Religious tolerance and the state -- t8. The intolerant personality -- t9. Education for tolerance -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligious intolerance is very old and widespread – a phenomenon of a highly distinctive nature which defies reduction to a simpler kind of vice. Methods of achieving religious tolerance have long been in dispute because there is much confusion about its nature.In this book, Professor Newman attempts to clarify the concept of religious tolerance in a way that other recent philosophical studies have clarified such concepts as justice, freedom, and equality. While there is a great deal of literature on theological, psychological, sociological, and political aspects of the problem, little has been said about the more fundamental ethical and epistemological issues that arise from philosophical reflection on religious competition and conflict.Newman addresses such questions as: How does religious intolerance differ from religious prejudice? Does being tolerant require commitment to relativism, pluralism, secularism, or universalism? Can a State live up to its promise to allow its citizens freedom of religion? Is intolerance a vice or a deep-rooted psychosis? Is it an inevitable by-product of education socialization? In shedding light on these and related problems, offering tentative solutions, and drawing on the writings of such philosophers as Aristotle, Aquinas, Spinoza, and Hume and such modern thinkers as Gordon Allport, Ronald Knox, and Walter Lippmann, Foundations of Religious Tolerance will assist clergymen, scholars, and laymen in their attempts to promote social harmony and mutual understanding among people of different faiths.This book will be especially useful in university courses and other programs in religious studies, philosophy, psychology, and sociology of religion, or that deal with prejudice and discrimination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFreedom of religion. 0aReligious tolerance. 7aRELIGION / Ethics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757775940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487577759423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487577759.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK